## Part I — Using Loom [packages/loom-lang]

You meet Loom the way you use it: by writing a document and watching it become code. This part is the whole surface a person touches, and nothing beneath it. It begins with a single loom and grows to a real project — sections composed with anchors and warps, one narrative spread across many files and languages, a workspace Loom sets up for you, and a command line that drives the rest. By the end you can build with Loom without yet knowing how it works inside.

Part I is not yet written. It is authored last, once the machine it introduces is settled, and folds in the guide that already teaches Loom from a first document up.

## Part II — How a loom becomes code

Now that you have written a loom, this part says what Loom did with it. It is the short path through the idea at the centre of the framework, and the map for every part that follows. Loom keeps two planes apart: the frame, the program that assembles your code, and the product, that code itself. It carries a loom along one pipeline from text to files, and the data flowing through is a single tree, the same shape at every stage. The rest of the book walks that pipeline one pass at a time.

Part II is not yet written. It is the overview, lifted from the architecture notes once the parts it maps are all in place.

## Part III — The shape of a loom

A loom is text, but Loom does not work on text. It works on a tree. This part is that tree — the data model every later pass reads and enriches. Every node shares one foundation. Each carries a place in the source and its own record of what is wrong with it. On that foundation stand three layers — the smallest tokens, the lines that group them, and the sections those lines form. Above them all sits the corpus, the modules that import one another.

::[The node foundation](03-the-shape-of-a-loom/the-node-foundation.loom)

::[The leaf tokens](03-the-shape-of-a-loom/the-leaf-tokens.loom)

::[Wefts](03-the-shape-of-a-loom/wefts.loom)

::[The container nodes](03-the-shape-of-a-loom/the-syntax-tree.loom)

::[The multi-file AST](03-the-shape-of-a-loom/the-corpus.loom)

## Part IV — Reading the text

A loom arrives as plain text, and Loom must read it into the tree the previous part described. This part is the reading. Four passes turn text into a tree: Loom finds the line boundaries, labels each line by what it is, fills in the pieces inside each line, and folds the labelled lines into a document of sections. A fifth pass follows that document's imports out to the corpus it belongs to.

::[Line ranges](04-reading-the-text/line-ranges.loom)

::[The classifier stage](04-reading-the-text/classifying-lines.loom)

::[The tokeniser stage](04-reading-the-text/tokenising.loom)

::[The document builder](04-reading-the-text/building-the-tree.loom)

::[Building one module](04-reading-the-text/following-imports.loom)

## Part V — The frame

Here the document turns into a program. Loom projects each section into a small composable unit, a service that carries the section's code, and wires the units into the frame — the program that assembles your code when it runs. The wiring comes from the document itself. A warp from one section to another is a dependency, and those dependencies fix the order. Running the frame produces the product — your code, composed at last into the files you meant to write.

::[The product pass](05-the-frame/the-product-pass.loom)

::[The de re structure](05-the-frame/the-product.loom)

## Part VI — Tangling

With your code produced, Loom writes it out. This part is the back half of the pipeline. The compiler works out where each file belongs, the tangler writes the files to disk, and the configuration — itself a loom — supplies the roots that place them. Loom refuses to write a build that still holds an unresolved reference, and when something is wrong, the author sees one plain message for it. A cache underneath keeps the next build fast.

::[The compile layer](06-tangling/the-compiler.loom)

